Description: [recto] Ad [Addendum] 1. Hafen von Neapel. cf. Vermeyen Conquest of Tunis Series. The piece with the 'Disembarkation at Goleta' (Madrid, [Albert Frederick] Calvert, [= The Spanish Royal Tapestries, London, New York: John Lane, 1921], Plate 35) (or is it Carthage?? Vienna 1862. Photo needed). See Vienna catalogue. High viewpoint. Ships decorative in foreground. The tapestries 1554 Studio Willem Pannemaker, completed, 1546 by Mary of Hungary commissioned to Vermeyen. Among Vermeyen's assistants according to Göbel: P. Coecke van Aelst. The tapestry cartoons in the time of Ernst & also early XVIII in Brussels; [verso] cf. also another see battle: Messina by Bruegel, Bastelaer 96. In several of these (Vienna 1868, 1869, 1870) Vermeyen is seen drawing cf. Bruegel, Etching of Landscape with Pysche and Mercury. Glück, Bruegel and Antiquity, [=Peter Brueghel the Elder and Classical Antiquity, in: Art Quarterly 6 (1943), pp. 167-186) p. 169 considers Bruegel to have been the first to introduce this motif, lent apart from Vermeyen it appears also the N.G.[National Gallery] picture (possibly Bruegel's prototype, but not by Bruegel) before Bruegel.
